===Glyph origin===
{{Han etym}}
{{Han compound|禾|朮|c1=s|c2=p|t1=grain|t2=glutinous millet|ls=psc}}. Originally written {{zh-l|*朮}} (not to be confused with {{zh-l|*术}}).

===Etymology 1===
{{zh-forms|alt=朮}}

Area word ({{zh-ref|Schuessler, 2007}}); compare:
* {{cog|hmx-pro|*mblut||glutinous; sticky}} ({{zh-ref|Sagart, 1999}}; {{zh-ref|Schuessler, 2007}}; {{zh-ref|Ratliff, 2010}}; {{zh-ref|Baxter and Sagart, 2014}});
* {{cog|map-pro|*-lit||caulk; adhesive material}} > {{cog|poz-pro|*bulit||glue; paste; stick; caulk}} ({{zh-ref|Ratliff, 2010}});
* {{cog|map-pro|*puluC||[[Caesar weed]], a [[mucilaginous]] plant}}, {{cog|poz-pro|*pulut||birdlime, sticky sap of breadfruit, etc.}} ({{zh-ref|Sagart, 1993}}; {{zh-ref|Ratliff, 2018}});
* {{cog|tbq-lob-pro|*C-lu-k||millet}} (STEDT).

{{zh-ref|Sagart and Baxter (2010)}} posit that the ''*m-'' in their {{cog|och|-}} reconstruction, based on the {{cog|hmx}} evidence, may be a reduced form of {{och-l|米|tr=*(C.)mˤ[e]jʔ|millet or rice grains, dehusked and polished}}.

